# The Sequence Approach
= (Developed by Frank Daniel & Paul Joseph Gulino.) Goal: To break a screenplay into 8 manageable "mini-movies," each with its own setup, tension, and resolution.

## Sequence 1: Status Quo & Inciting Incident (Act I)
= Introduces the protagonist and their world. Ends with the inciting incident that disrupts their status quo.

## Sequence 2: Predicament & Lock In (Act I)
= The protagonist attempts to deal with the inciting incident. Ends with a decision or commitment that locks them into the main conflict, ending Act I.

## Sequence 3: First Obstacle & Raising the Stakes (Act II)
= The protagonist makes their first, often easiest, attempt to solve the central problem. New stakes are established.

## Sequence 4: First Culmination / Midpoint (Act II)
= New complications arise; the first attempt fails or creates a larger problem. Ends with a major shift or midpoint reversal.

## Sequence 5: Subplot & Rising Action (Act II)
= Often involves a deeper dive into the "special world" of the story, exploring subplots or a shift in strategy.

## Sequence 6: Main Culmination / End of Act II (Act II)
= The stakes are raised to their highest. Ends with the climax of Act II, often a moment where "all hope is lost" or the highest point of tension.

## Sequence 7: New Tension & Twist (Act III)
= The protagonist grapples with the fallout of the Act II climax. A new plan is formed, or a twist propels them toward the final confrontation.

## Sequence 8: Resolution (Act III)
= The final battle or climax of the entire story, followed by the actual resolution and the establishment of a new status quo.
